In the case of a mortgage of copyhold land (the present survival of the old feudal tenure) the very same roundabout system of a “ surrender '' with an accompanying “ deed of cove- nants” is the method in use at this moment. In a freehold mortgage the covenants or provisos are in the same deed. At this day a date is always fixed for repayment—the conveyanee becoming absolute after that day if default be made, as it always is. The mortgagee would receive the rents and profits instead of interest (which was not allowed until Henry V111.‘s time, i.e. by law). The peculiarity of this indenture is the fixing of three days, peculiarly lenient to the mortgagor.
